 Dordogne, Aquitaine, France":"Calais, Dordogne, Aquitaine, Frankrijk","Elwaston Manor, Derbyshire, England":"Elvaston, Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1355–Aft 1392":"1355–after 1392","1346–1392":"1346–1392","1355–1392":"1355–1392","1350–1403":"1350–1403","1370–1425":"1370–1425","1340–Male":"1340–Deceased","1322–1369":"1322–1369","1328–1391":"1328–1391","2 October 1369":"2 October 1369","13 june 1391":"13 June 1391","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1392":"1392","1391":"1391","1425":"1425","1403":"1403","1369":"1369","1346":"1346","1345":"1345","1355":"1355","1322":"1322","Aft 1392":"after 1392","1328":"1328","Hatch, Somerset, England":"Hatch, Somerset, England","Hestercombe, Somerset, England":"Hestercombe, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, England":"Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, England","Calais, Dordogne, Aquitaine, France":"Calais, Dordogne, Aquitaine, France","Elwaston Manor, Derbyshire, England":"Elvaston, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Meriet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: derivative of <i>merle</i> ‘blackbird’ (see   Merle  ). Compare   Marlette  .","History: Gédéon Merlet/Marlet from Roussy-le-Village in Moselle, France, married Margriet Martijn in Leiden, the Netherlands, in 1644, died in Piscataway, NJ, <i>c.</i> 1682. In 1662 they emigrated to the Dutch colony of New Amsterdam in New Netherland (now New York City, NY). Gédéon's name is listed (as Gidéon Merlet) in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."],"variants":[{"name":"Marlette","meanings":["Americanized form of French <b>Marlet</b> or of its variant   Merlet  . Altered ending reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>. Compare   Malott  ,   Malotte  ,   Marlatt  ,   Marlett  ,   Mellott  , and   Melott  .","History: Gédéon Merlet/Marlet from Roussy-le-Village in Moselle, France, married Margriet Martijn in Leiden, the Netherlands, in 1644, died in Piscataway, NJ, <i>c.</i> 1682. In 1662 they emigrated to the Dutch colony of New Amsterdam in New Netherland (now New York City, NY). Gédéon's name is listed (as Gidéon Merlet) in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."]},{"name":"Merle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Etienne, Henri, Jean-Paul.","French, English (of Norman origin), German, and Dutch: nickname, possibly for a good or habitual singer or whistler, from Old French, Middle High German <i>merle</i> ‘blackbird’ (from Latin <i>merula</i>). See also Italian and Spanish   Merlo  .","French: habitational name from (Le) Merle, the name of several places in various parts of France."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":27,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Eleanor de Meriet was born in 1355, in Hatch, Somerset, England, her father, Sir John de Meriet I, was 33 and her mother, Eleanor de Beauchamp, was 27. She had at least 1 son with John de la Warre. She died after 1392, in Hestercombe, Somerset, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1355–Aft 1392":"1355–pärast 1392","1346–1392":"1346–1392","1355–1392":"1355–1392","1350–1403":"1350–1403","1370–1425":"1370–1425","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1322–1369":"1322–1369","1328–1391":"1328–1391","2 October 1369":"2. oktoober 1369","13 june 1391":"13. juuni 1391","1340":"1340","1350"